Your error:

open /dev/ptmx: no space left on device

is usually caused by exhaustion of PTYs (pseudo terminals) on the node, not disk space.

Common root causes in OpenShift / CRI-O environments are:


---

1. Too many exec/rsh sessions (Most common)

Repeated usage of:

oc rsh

oc exec

crictl exec


can leave stale PTY allocations if sessions disconnect improperly.

Especially common when:

terminal/network disconnects

automation/scripts run many execs

shells crash



---

2. Stale conmon processes

conmon manages container stdio for CRI-O.

Sometimes after:

failed execs

runtime glitches

container crashes


old conmon processes remain alive and keep PTYs allocated.

Check:

ps -ef | grep conmon | wc -l


---

3. Kernel PTY limit reached

Linux has a maximum PTY count.

Check:

sysctl kernel.pty.nr
sysctl kernel.pty.max

If:

nr ≈ max


then new terminal allocation fails.

Typical defaults:

max = 4096


Long-running clusters sometimes leak PTYs over days/weeks.


---

4. File descriptor exhaustion

Each exec consumes file descriptors.

Check:

cat /proc/sys/fs/file-nr

and:

ulimit -n


---

5. CRI-O bug / runtime leak

This is also seen in:

older CRI-O builds

long uptime SNO clusters

heavy debugging environments


Runtime gradually leaks PTYs/resources until restart.


---

Why restart fixes it

Restarting crio:

clears stale exec sessions

releases leaked PTYs

restarts conmon

resets runtime state


That is why it is the standard fix.


---

To confirm after recovery, run:

sysctl kernel.pty.nr

If the number drops significantly after restart, PTY leakage/exhaustion was the cause.
